2025-12-11 02:42:11.452 | WARNING  | agentscope.message.msg:__init__:145 - A new field `role` is newly added to the message. Please specify the role of the message. Currently we use a default "assistant" value.Scientist0: Thought: The core challenge in entity linking—particularly in handling NIL (Not In Linkable Knowledge Base) predictions—lies in the model’s ability to distinguish between entities that are merely rare or out-of-vocabulary and those that genuinely do not correspond to any known entry in the knowledge base. Existing models often overfit to non-NIL examples due to imbalanced training data and lack a principled way of assessing the "plausibility" of a mention referring to a known entity. Drawing inspiration from Papers 1 and 2, which emphasize prototype-based reasoning and faithful similarity interpretation, I propose a novel framework that shifts the focus from direct classification to plausibility assessment via asymmetric comparison in a prototypical space. Unlike prior work that treats all prototypes symmetrically, my idea introduces *asymmetric* prototype learning where known-entity prototypes are fixed as anchors, while NIL instances are modeled as deviations beyond a learned plausibility margin. This enables robust generalization by learning what makes an entity mention *implausible* as a linkable reference. Furthermore, by integrating a meta-learning strategy for adaptive thresholding, the model avoids rigid decision boundaries and dynamically adjusts to domain-specific ambiguity. This approach is distinct from RuleNN (Paper 3), which focuses on symbolic rule extraction, and instead offers a continuous, geometrically interpretable solution grounded in representation learning. The resulting framework not only improves NIL detection but also provides explainability through prototype alignment analysis, answering *why* a mention was deemed unlinkable.

